description:
Pattern at secretx-pkcs11/src/lib.rs:90, 95, 102, 109, 141, 168, 207, 215, 231, 239, 266, 330, 402, 416, 491, 502, 539:

.map_err(|e| SecretError::Backend {
    backend: "pkcs11",
    source: e.into(),
})

17 occurrences of the same 4 lines. The 'pkcs11' literal repeats, the source: e.into() conversion repeats, and the structure is purely mechanical.

Suggested rewrite: a tiny extension trait or helper at top of file:

const BACKEND: &str = "pkcs11";

trait Pkcs11ResultExt<T> {
    fn pkcs11(self) -> Result<T, SecretError>;
}

impl<T, E> Pkcs11ResultExt<T> for Result<T, E>
where E: Into<Box<dyn std::error::Error + Send + Sync + 'static>>
{
    fn pkcs11(self) -> Result<T, SecretError> {
        self.map_err(|e| SecretError::Backend {
            backend: BACKEND,
            source: e.into(),
        })
    }
}

Then each call site becomes:
    ctx.initialize(args).pkcs11()?;

If finding crate-secretsx-nde2.2 (Backend vs Unavailable mapping) lands, this extension trait is the natural place for the classification logic. Defer this finding until .2 is decided so we don't refactor twice.

Note also: secretx-wolfhsm/src/lib.rs:60 already uses the const BACKEND: &str pattern. Workspace consistency favors adopting the same here.
